<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720654a682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:17.</label.designator><headtext>Dying declarations</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER804" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I453411307fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 804(b)(2)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-804" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I453411317fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-804(b)(2)</cite.query> provide the hearsay exception for dying declarations. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-804" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I453411327fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-804(b)(2)</cite.query> states that, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“in a prosecution for homicide or in a civil proceeding, a statement made by a declarant while believing that his or her death was imminent, concerning the cause or circumstances of what the declarant believed to be impending death”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> is not excluded by the hearsay rule.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The judge, not the jury, makes the final determination as to whether the exception applies,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic53d9fe07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] the rule extends the hearsay exception to civil cases,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic53d9fe17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] and contemplates admission of a dying declaration when the declarant is, in fact, not dead.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53d9fe27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The rule only requires “unavailability” of the witness, but, at the time when he made the statement, the declarant must have believed that his death was imminent.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53d9fe37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The dying declaration was admissible into evidence long before the rule excluding hearsay developed. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1959125083" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I4536d0527fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Ayers v. State</ital></cite.query> contains a good discussion of the dying declaration exception.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dc6f07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A declarant must have firsthand knowledge of the facts that he is stating,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic53dc6f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] and any question as to whether the declaration is based on knowledge of the declarant is for the jury to decide.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dc6f27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Georgia excludes dying declarations that are opinions or conclusions,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic53dc6f37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] but the Georgia Supreme Court has not strictly defined opinion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dc6f47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The dying declaration may be made in reply to questions and <page no="308"/>may be made by signs or nodding the head.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dee007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] For example, a victim&apos;s hand signals identifying his assailant are admissible under this exception.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dee017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A dying declaration must have been made <ital>in articulo mortis</ital>, which may be shown by the circumstances, the apparent fatal quality of the wound, and the deceased&apos;s belief that he was dying.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dee027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>] However, a dying declaration is not required to contain any statement by the deceased to that he was conscious of impending death at the time when the declarations were made.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dee037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13</footnote.reference>] Also, the test is declarant&apos;s belief in impending death, not the actual swiftness with which death ensued.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53dee047fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14</footnote.reference>] This is a jury question, but cases have approved long periods of time after the declaration before death actually ensued, even up to 3<fraction><numerator>1</numerator><denominator>2</denominator></fraction> months.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53e15107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">15</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A dying declaration is admissible on behalf of an accused as well as against him. <eos/><bos/>The self-serving or disserving feature of a <page no="309"/>dying declaration is no part of the basis of the exception. <eos/><bos/>The dying declaration may indicate the innocence of the criminal defendant and is admissible for that purpose.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic53e15117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">16</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic53d9fe07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1998101442" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="I453486617fc011ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. Rivera-Figueroa, 149 F.3d 1, 49 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 343 (1st Cir. 1998)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-1-104" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I453486667fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-1-104(a)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53d9fe17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-804" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I4534d4807fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-804(b)(2)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1991058395" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I453522a17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Pau v. Yosemite Park and Curry Co., 928 F.2d 880, 33 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 478, 19 Fed. R. Serv. 3d 1487, 14 U.C.C. Rep. Serv. 2d 79 (9th Cir. 1991)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1985112638" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I453522a87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Pfeil v. Rogers, 757 F.2d 850, 17 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 823, 1 Fed. R. Serv. 3d 1219 (7th Cir. 1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53d9fe27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See Advisory Committee Notes, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER804" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I453597d07fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 804</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“Unavailability is not limited to death”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53d9fe37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER804" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I45360d007fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 804(b)(2)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1933123159" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I45360d037fc011ea988285db8533e975">Shepard v. U.S., 290 U.S. 96, 54 S. Ct. 22, 78 L. Ed. 196 (1933)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dc6f07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1959125083" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I4536f7627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ayers v. State, 215 Ga. 325, 110 S.E.2d 669 (1959)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dc6f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1929105648" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I45376c927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Strickland v. State, 167 Ga. 452, 145 S.E. 879 (1928)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dc6f27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1953105152" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I4537bab27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bland v. State, 210 Ga. 100, 78 S.E.2d 51 (1953)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dc6f37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1897009647" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I45382fe27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Kearney v. State, 101 Ga. 803, 29 S.E. 127 (1897)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dc6f47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1897010155" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I4538a5127fc011ea988285db8533e975">White v. State, 100 Ga. 659, 28 S.E. 423 (1897)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1922105573" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I4538a5157fc011ea988285db8533e975">Green v. State, 154 <page no="308"/>Ga. 117, 113 S.E. 536 (1922)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1929105648" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I4538a5187fc011ea988285db8533e975">Strickland v. State, 167 Ga. 452, 145 S.E. 879 (1928)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1979106096" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I4538a51b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Dixon v. State, 243 Ga. 46, 252 S.E.2d 431 (1979)</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“She didn&apos;t have to do it”<end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1985130066" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453941527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Wright v. State, 254 Ga. 484, 489, 330 S.E.2d 358 (1985)</cite.query>: <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“Where it is manifestly impossible that the deceased could have seen his assailant or known certainly who he was, a mere expression of opinion as to who he was is not admissible as a dying declaration; but where want of knowledge does not appear either from the statement itself or from other evidence in the case, it must be presumed that the declarant stated a fact within his knowledge.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dee007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1953105152" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I45398f727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bland v. State, 210 Ga. 100, 78 S.E.2d 51 (1953)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dee017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1988087879" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453a04a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Richie v. State, 258 Ga. 361, 369 S.E.2d 740 (1988)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="2034353204" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453a04a57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Wiggins v. State, 295 Ga. 684, 763 S.E.2d 484 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dee027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1953105152" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453a79d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bland v. State, 210 Ga. 100, 78 S.E.2d 51 (1953)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1959125083" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453a79d57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ayers v. State, 215 Ga. 325, 110 S.E.2d 669 (1959)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1970134822" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453a79d87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Francis v. State, 121 Ga. App. 256, 173 S.E.2d 710 (1970)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1982117502" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453aef027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Andrews v. State, 249 Ga. 223, 290 S.E.2d 71 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1982131672" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453b64327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Holcomb v. State, 249 Ga. 658, 292 S.E.2d 839 (1982)</cite.query>, the court considered the question of impending death. <eos/><bos/>The declaration would be admissible if: <begin.quote ID="QT_0005"/>“(1) The victim was in ‘the article of death’ at the time the statement was made; and (2) he was aware that he was in the article of death.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0005"/> The trial judge had admitted the declaration but was in error in failing to properly charge the jury.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Murder victim&apos;s statement identifying the defendant as the shooter was admissible as dying declaration even though the doctor reassured the victim about his condition and the victim survived four days after being shot. <eos/><bos/>The victim had been shot in the top of the head and was found gurgling in a pool of his own blood. <eos/><bos/>The victim could barely speak, and the nature of his statement suggested that he believed he might not survive. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="2017859583" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453c27827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Barnett v. State, 284 Ga. 781, 671 S.E.2d 823 (2009)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dee037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="2002329488" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453c75a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Morgan v. State, 275 Ga. 222, 564 S.E.2d 192 (2002)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="2005909324" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453c75a57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Woodard v. State, 278 Ga. 827, 607 S.E.2d 592 (2005)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53dee047fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1984130551" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453cead27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Early v. State, 170 Ga. App. 158, 316 S.E.2d 527 (1984)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53e15107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1970135892" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453d87127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ward v. State, 226 Ga. 724, 177 S.E.2d 378 (1970)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1936107134" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I453d87157fc011ea988285db8533e975">Miles v. State, 182 Ga. 75, 185 S.E. 286 (1936)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1943104842" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453d87187fc011ea988285db8533e975">Emmett v. State, 195 Ga. 517, 25 S.E.2d 9 (1943)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1976136054" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453d871b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Howard v. State, 237 Ga. 471, 228 S.E.2d 860 (1976)</cite.query>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1950104724" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I453d871e7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Stembridge v. State, 82 Ga. App. 214, 60 S.E.2d 491 (1950)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="309"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic53e15117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>16</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1910011967" w-seq-number="00039" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I453e4a627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Flanagan v. State, 135 Ga. 221, 69 S.E. 171 (1910)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017176" w-serial-number="1930105683" w-seq-number="00040" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I453e4a657fc011ea988285db8533e975">Johnson v. State, 169 Ga. 814, 152 S.E. 76 (1930)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
